cal papers to private letters and visual material—Hussin offers a view of politics in the colonial period as an iterative series of negotiations between local and colonial powers in multiple locations. She shows how this resulted in a paradox, centralizing Islamic law at the same time that it limited its reach to family and ritual matters, and produced a transformation in the Muslim state, providing the frame within which Islam is articulated today, setting the agenda for ongoing legislation and policy, and defining the limits of change. Combining a genealogy of law with a political analysis of its institutional dynamics, this book offers an up-close look at the ways in which global transformations are realized at the local level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIslam and politics. 0aIslam and state. 0aIslamic lawxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aislam, muslim, theocracy, nation, politics, religion, power, authority, colonialism, law, india, malaya, egypt, british empire, shariah, court records, letters, government, centralization, jurisdiction, representation, race, ethnicity, prejudice, bias, discrimination, control, state, violence, postcolonialism, malaysia, courts, legal codes, treaties, census, maps, newspapers, nonfiction, history, political science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226323480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226323480/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles